## Diagnosis

The ETRO essay renderer is faithfully passing through every `**bold**` span from the source markdown without editorial filtering. The author used bold as a **scanning device** (labelling paragraph openers like "Per user.", "Scaffolding.", "Note:") rather than for semantic emphasis. Meanwhile the section hierarchy feels flat because those bold labels are doing the visual work that **headings and spacing** should do.

Two compounding problems:

1. **Content layer** — 36 bold spans in body copy, most functioning as pseudo-headings or run-in labels.
2. **Presentation layer** — section breaks rely only on paragraph spacing; no typographic hierarchy differentiates sections from paragraphs.

Anti-pattern: **AP-072** (presentational markdown leaking into semantic HTML) and **EAP-027** (typographic hierarchy collapse — bold substituted for heading levels).

---

## Root Cause

### AP-072 · Presentational markdown leaking into semantic HTML

The Payload rich-text field (or the MDX/markdown source) stores author-intent formatting verbatim. The renderer (`<RichText>` or `<MDXContent>`) maps every `**…**` node → `<strong>` with no post-processing pass to distinguish:

- **Semantic bold** (a term being defined, a proper noun)
- **Scan-anchor bold** (a run-in label the author used as a substitute heading)

### EAP-027 · Typographic hierarchy collapse

The prose container gives paragraphs uniform spacing and no visual section landmarks, so without the bold labels the reader has no navigational cues at all — the bold is load-bearing even though it shouldn't be.

---

## Fix

Three coordinated changes:

### 1. Serialiser / renderer — strip scan-anchor bold, promote run-in labels

The correct long-term fix is to convert run-in label bold spans into proper `<h3>` / `<h4>` elements at the data layer (in Payload, retrain authors). Short-term, intercept at the serialiser.

**`src/components/RichText/serialisers.tsx`** (or wherever your Lexical/Slate node map lives):

```tsx
// Before — naive pass-through
strong: ({ children }) => <strong>{children}</strong>,

// After — detect scan-anchor pattern and demote
strong: ({ children, node }) => {
  const text = typeof children === 'string'
    ? children
    : Array.isArray(children)
      ? children.map(c => (typeof c === 'string' ? c : '')).join('')
      : '';

  /**
   * Scan-anchor detection:
   *   • Ends with a period or colon  →  was used as a run-in label
   *   • All-caps abbreviation        →  acronym, keep bold
   *   • Single word + period ≤ 20 ch →  high confidence label
   *
   * Demote to plain text so the prose styles handle weight naturally.
   * If you later want these as subheadings, swap <span> for <h4>.
   */
  const isRunInLabel =
    /^[A-Z][^a-z]{0,2}[a-z].{0,30}[.:]$/.test(text.trim()) ||
    /^\w[\w\s]{0,18}[.:]$/.test(text.trim());

  if (isRunInLabel) {
    // Option A: plain text (removes emphasis entirely)
    return <span>{children}</span>;

    // Option B: promote to semantic subheading (uncomment if preferred)
    // return (
    //   <h4 className="font-semibold text-base mt-6 mb-1 text-foreground">
    //     {children}
    //   </h4>
    // );
  }

  return <strong>{children}</strong>;
},
```

> **Decision point:** Option A is the minimalist fix (no visual change, just stops the weight abuse). Option B promotes the labels to real heading nodes — pick whichever matches editorial intent. If you promote, also add them to any table-of-contents generator.

---

### 2. Prose typography — section hierarchy via spacing + a subtle rule

**`src/components/RichText/RichText.module.css`** (or your Tailwind prose overrides):

```css
/* ─── Elan prose overrides for long-form essays ─── */

/* Give h2 sections room to breathe and a thin top rule */
.prose :is(h2) {
  margin-block-start: 3rem;        /* was: likely 1.5rem from @tailwindcss/typography */
  padding-block-start: 1.25rem;
  border-block-start: 1px solid var(--color-border-subtle);  /* Elan token */
  font-size: var(--text-xl);
  font-weight: 600;
  letter-spacing: -0.01em;
}

/* h3 gets breathing room but no rule — subordinate but distinct */
.prose :is(h3) {
  margin-block-start: 2rem;
  font-size: var(--text-lg);
  font-weight: 550;                /* variable font mid-weight, not bold */
}

/* h4 run-in labels (Option B above) */
.prose :is(h4) {
  margin-block-start: 1.5rem;
  margin-block-end: 0.25rem;
  font-size: var(--text-base);
  font-weight: 500;
  color: var(--color-foreground-muted);
  text-transform: none;
}

/* Tighten strong — only true semantic emphasis gets full 700 */
.prose strong {
  font-weight: 600;                /* down from browser default 700 */
  color: inherit;                  /* don't shift hue on emphasis */
}

/* Paragraph spacing — generous for essay reading */
.prose p {
  margin-block-end: 1.25em;       /* was probably 1em */
}
```

---

### 3. Payload CMS — field-level validation to prevent recurrence

**`src/collections/Essays/fields/body.ts`**:

```ts
import type { RichTextField } from 'payload/types';

export const bodyField: RichTextField = {
  name: 'body',
  type: 'richText',
  // ... existing config ...
  admin: {
    description:
      'Use bold only for semantic emphasis on terms or proper nouns. ' +
      'Use Heading 3 / Heading 4 for section labels. ' +
      'Do not use bold as a paragraph opener / scan anchor.',
  },
  validate: (value) => {
    // Walk the Lexical node tree and count bold leaf nodes
    let boldCount = 0;
    const walk = (nodes: any[]) => {
      for (const node of nodes ?? []) {
        if (node.format & 1) boldCount++; // Lexical bold flag = bit 0
        if (node.children) walk(node.children);
      }
    };
    walk(value?.root?.children ?? []);

    if (boldCount > 12) {
      return `This body has ${boldCount} bold spans. Elan editorial standard is ≤ 12. ` +
             'Convert run-in labels to headings.';
    }
    return true;
  },
};
```

> The threshold (12) is intentionally loose — a 7-section essay can legitimately bold a couple of key terms per section. Tighten if needed.

---

## Principle

**Formatting is not hierarchy.** Bold weight signals *semantic importance* within a sentence; heading level signals *structural position* within a document. When authors use bold as a heading substitute (AP-072) they simultaneously overload the emphasis signal and flatten the visible structure (EAP-027). The correct fix is not a CSS patch — it is restoring the correct node types at the serialiser or data layer, then letting the design system's typographic scale handle visual hierarchy. CSS is a downstream amplifier; it cannot compensate for structurally wrong HTML.
